{"title_page": "James R. Garrison", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = James R. Garrison\n|image         = \n|caption       = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1838|6|22}}\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1908|4|19|1838|6|22}}\n|birth_place   = [[Poughkeepsie, New York]]\n|death_place   = \n|placeofburial = [[Hampton National Cemetery]], [[Hampton, Virginia]]\n|placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n|placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|allegiance    = [[United States]]\n|branch        = [[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears  = \n|rank          = Coal Heaver\n|unit          = {{flagicon|United States Navy}} {{USS|Hartford|1858|6}}\n|battles       = [[American Civil War]]<br/>{{*}} [[Battle of Mobile Bay]]\n|awards        = [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\n'''James R. Garrison''' (June 22, 1838 \u2013 April 19, 1908) was a [[Union Navy]] sailor in the [[American Civil War]] and a recipient of the U.S. military's highest decoration, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his actions at the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]].\n\nBorn on June 22, 1838, in [[Poughkeepsie, New York]], Garrison was still living in that state when he joined the Navy. He served during the Civil War as a coal heaver on Admiral [[David Farragut]]'s flagship, the {{USS|Hartford|1858|6}}. At the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]] on August 5, 1864, he lost a toe to Confederate fire but continued his duties at the shell whip (a device used to lift ammunition up to the [[gun deck]]) until receiving a second, severe, wound. For this action, he was awarded the Medal of Honor four months later, on December 31, 1864.<ref name=\"hallofvalor\"/><ref name=\"citation\"/>\n\nGarrison's official Medal of Honor citation reads:\n<blockquote>On board the flagship, U.S.S. ''Hartford'', during successful engagements against [[Fort Morgan (Alabama)|Fort Morgan]], rebel gunboats and the ram ''[[CSS Tennessee (1863)|Tennessee]]'' in Mobile Bay, on 5 August 1864. When a shell struck his foot and severed one of his toes, Garrison remained at his station at the shell whip and, after crudely bandaging the wound, continued to perform his duties until severely wounded by another shellburst.<ref name=\"citation\"/></blockquote>\n\nGarrison died on April 19, 1908, at age 69 and was buried at [[Hampton National Cemetery]] in [[Hampton, Virginia]].<ref name=\"hallofvalor\"/><ref name=\"usdva\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"hallofvalor\">{{Hallofvalor|1628|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"citation\">{{Cite web\n  | title       = Civil War Medal of Honor Recipients (A\u2013L)\n  | work        = Medal of Honor Citations\n  | publisher   = [[United States Army Center of Military History]]\n  | date        = June 26, 2011\n  | url         = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/civwaral.html\n  | accessdate  = October 17, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"usdva\">{{Cite web\n  | title      = Hampton National Cemetery\n  | publisher  = [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]]\n  | date       = August 13, 2012\n  | url        = http://www.cem.va.gov/cems/nchp/hampton.asp\n  | accessdate = October 17, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Find a Grave|7895116}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrison, James R.}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Poughkeepsie, New York]]\n[[Category:People of New York (state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:United States Navy Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = James R. Garrison\n|image         = \n|caption       = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1838|6|22}}\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1908|4|19|1838|6|22}}\n|birth_place   = [[Poughkeepsie, New York]]\n|death_place   = \n|placeofburial = [[Hampton National Cemetery]], [[Hampton, Virginia]]\n|placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n|placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|allegiance    = [[United States]]\n|branch        = [[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears  = \n|rank          = Coal Heaver\n|unit          = {{USS|Hartford|1858|6}}\n|battles       = [[American Civil War]]<br/>{{*}} [[Battle of Mobile Bay]]\n|awards        = [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\n'''James R. Garrison''' (June 22, 1838 \u2013 April 19, 1908) was a [[Union Navy]] sailor in the [[American Civil War]] and a recipient of the U.S. military's highest decoration, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his actions at the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]].\n\nBorn on June 22, 1838, in [[Poughkeepsie, New York]], Garrison was still living in that state when he joined the Navy. He served during the Civil War as a coal heaver on Admiral [[David Farragut]]'s flagship, the {{USS|Hartford|1858|6}}. At the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]] on August 5, 1864, he lost a toe to Confederate fire but continued his duties at the shell whip (a device used to lift ammunition up to the [[gun deck]]) until receiving a second, severe, wound. For this action, he was awarded the Medal of Honor four months later, on December 31, 1864.<ref name=\"hallofvalor\"/><ref name=\"citation\"/>\n\nGarrison's official Medal of Honor citation reads:\n<blockquote>On board the flagship, U.S.S. ''Hartford'', during successful engagements against [[Fort Morgan (Alabama)|Fort Morgan]], rebel gunboats and the ram ''[[CSS Tennessee (1863)|Tennessee]]'' in Mobile Bay, on 5 August 1864. When a shell struck his foot and severed one of his toes, Garrison remained at his station at the shell whip and, after crudely bandaging the wound, continued to perform his duties until severely wounded by another shellburst.<ref name=\"citation\"/></blockquote>\n\nGarrison died on April 19, 1908, at age 69 and was buried at [[Hampton National Cemetery]] in [[Hampton, Virginia]].<ref name=\"hallofvalor\"/><ref name=\"usdva\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"hallofvalor\">{{Hallofvalor|1628|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"citation\">{{Cite web\n  | title       = Civil War Medal of Honor Recipients (A\u2013L)\n  | work        = Medal of Honor Citations\n  | publisher   = [[United States Army Center of Military History]]\n  | date        = June 26, 2011\n  | url         = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/civwaral.html\n  | accessdate  = October 17, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"usdva\">{{Cite web\n  | title      = Hampton National Cemetery\n  | publisher  = [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]]\n  | date       = August 13, 2012\n  | url        = http://www.cem.va.gov/cems/nchp/hampton.asp\n  | accessdate = October 17, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Find a Grave|7895116}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrison, James R.}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Poughkeepsie, New York]]\n[[Category:People of New York (state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:United States Navy Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_R._Garrison"}
{"title_page": "Nova Scotia killings", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size1       = 8\n|      label1      = Portapique\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.3972|-63.7067}}\n|  label-pos1      = left\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = [[Portapique, Nova Scotia]]\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n\n|      label2      = Wentworth\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|45.6564|-63.5493}}\n|mark-title2       = [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label3      = Debert\n|       mark3      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3       = 8\n|  label-pos3      = right\n| label-size3      = 10\n|label-color3      = black\n| mark-coord3      = {{coord|45.4197|-63.4313}}\n|mark-title3       = [[Debert, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label4      = Shubenacadie\n|       mark4      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4       = 8\n|  label-pos4      = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label5      = Enfield\n|       mark5      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size5       = 8\n|  label-pos5      = left\n| label-size5      = 10\n|label-color5      = black\n| mark-coord5      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title5       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18|10|26 p.m.}} \u2013 <br> {{end date|2020|4|19|11|26 a.m.}} [[Atlantic Daylight Time|ADT]]\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass murder]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = 23<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/portapique-shooting-memorials-april-21-1.5539894|title=22 victims confirmed dead in N.S. mass shooting|publisher=CBC News|first=Taryn|last=Grant|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| injuries         = 2<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--><ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Unknown (under investigation)\n}}\nOver a thirteen-hour period spanning April 18\u201319, 2020, a [[killing spree]] took place at various locations in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]]. Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old man, killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people and set fire to five buildings before he was intercepted and killed by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP).<ref name=\"CBC10\"/><ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=22 victims of N.S. rampage include retirees, pregnant health care worker, veteran|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest rampage in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob |publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The RCMP has yet to establish a motive.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===April 18===\nBeginning at around 10:26 p.m., several residents of the rural beachside community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], called [[9-1-1]] to report gunshots and several fires.<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=CBC News|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-new-details-timeline-nova-scotia-manhunt-1.5541561|title=RCMP give new details on timeline of manhunt for N.S. shooter|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\"/><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead in Nova Scotia shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> [[ABC News]], citing unnamed investigators, reported that the incident may have begun as a case of [[domestic violence]] at a house where Wortman was trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"ABC2\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/death-toll-nova-scotia-shooting-rampage-increases-19/story?id=70251470|title=Nova Scotia shooting may have begun as a domestic violence dispute: Investigators|publisher=ABC News|last1=Deliso|first1=Meredith|last2=Pereira|first2=Ivan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA source told [[CNN]] that Wortman burned down his own house before going to his former partner's residence, where he killed people living there and also nearby.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> When RCMP officers arrived on the scene twelve minutes later, at around 10:38 p.m., three houses on Portapique Beach Road and Orchard Beach Drive were found burning. Thirteen victims were soon located, who had reportedly been shot after fleeing the fires. One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they could not locate an armed suspect and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/nova-scotia-shooting-manhunt-details-1.5542025|title='They don't know if they've caught him': Recordings reveal chaos of Nova Scotia manhunt|publisher=CBC News|last=Gatehouse|first=Jonathon|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":5\"/>\n\nConfusion persisted for hours over whether a suspect had been apprehended.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> At 11:32 p.m., the RCMP posted a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked and officers set up a search perimeter in the Portapique area. As the investigation developed overnight, they determined that the suspect had eluded them.<ref name=\":4\" /> By the morning of April 19, they said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=MassLive}}</ref>\n\n===April 19===\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported an explosion and gunfire at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Gabriel Wortman as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was impersonating a police officer by wearing an RCMP uniform and driving a replica police vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was seen in or near the communities of [[Glenholme, Nova Scotia|Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Onslow, Nova Scotia|Onslow]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating that he was travelling toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-timeline-of-nova-scotia-mass-shooting/|title=Timeline of Nova Scotia mass shooting|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> At 10:54 a.m., surveillance video apparently captured Wortman pulling into a parking lot in [[Millbrook 27|Millbrook First Nation]] in the mock police vehicle, briefly getting out to put on a reflective vest, and then driving off.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boynton|first=Sean|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6855907/nova-scotia-mass-shooting-new-video/|title=Video appears to show Nova Scotia shooting suspect stop, change clothes amid killing spree|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=Global News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> During this time, Wortman performed three [[Traffic stop|traffic stops]] on random cars and killed their occupants.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nAt approximately 11:15 a.m., RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson encountered Wortman oncoming on [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Route 2]] in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]], and rammed her cruiser into his replica to stop it.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/20/nova-scotia-shooting-details-emerge-in-gabriel-wortmans-rampage/|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Details emerge in suspect Gabriel Wortman's rampage|last=Sheehy|first=Kate|date=April 20, 2020|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|archive-date=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Witnesses reported that Wortman exited his vehicle and shot into Stevenson's, killing her and injuring another officer.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> Both cars also caught fire, though accounts differ as to when and how.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> Wortman then stole a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] from a nearby motorist, and was next seen continuing south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] through [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]] at 11:24 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThirteen hours after police began pursuing him, at 11:26 a.m., Wortman was finally intercepted, shot, and killed by at least one officer at the [[Irving Oil#Big Stops|Irving Big Stop]] [[Rest area|service area]] in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> His death was confirmed by police at 11:40 a.m.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people, including Constable Heidi Stevenson. He shot another officer, who survived.<ref name=\"CBC10\" /><ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> One other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> Victims were found in the communities of Portapique, Wentworth, Debert, Shubenacadie/Milford and Enfield.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|title=Canada shooting: Death toll in Nova Scotia rises to 22|publisher=BBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422000411/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nAccording to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of Wortman's first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, those he attacked became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' reported that Wortman had created a list of people to target, although not all those on the list were attacked. The newspaper noted that the two victims at the home in Wentworth were known to Wortman because one had previously gone hunting with him.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Perpetrator==\n [[File:Atlantic Denture Clinic (3).jpg|thumb|Workers removing signage from the perpetrator's denture clinic in Dartmouth on April 22]]\n\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer, his [[yearbook]] entry alluding to this.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020|last=Frisko|first=Bruce}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a polite and [[Wiktionary:house-proud#English|house-proud]] man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman pleaded guilty to assault in 2002 and was sentenced to nine months of probation, in which he was prohibited from possessing weapons and ordered to undergo anger management counselling.<ref name=\"CTV6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rcmp-say-they-were-in-process-of-preparing-alert-when-gunman-was-killed-1.4906672|title=N.S. RCMP say they were 'in process' of preparing alert when gunman was killed|publisher=CTV News|last=Flanagan|first=Ryan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC8\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-criminal-record-1.5541176|title=Suspect in N.S. killings didn't have criminal record, but previously pleaded guilty to a crime|publisher=CBC News|last=Donkin|first=Karissa|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> He was also involved in two civil matters regarding property disputes, according to interviews and public records. A former acquaintance described how, in 2004, Wortman offered to help him when he had financial difficulties and was about to lose his house, only for Wortman to discreetly take ownership of the home away from him, evict him, and sell the property. In 2015, Wortman had been temporarily loaned a Portapique home a paternal uncle had purchased while he was in the process of selling his [[Edmonton]] condominium. Wortman refused to release the Portapique property back to him, claiming he was owed money, until the uncle eventually sold it.<ref name=\"CBC8\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6846920/nova-scotia-killer-financial-practices/|title='He stole my house': Nova Scotia killer had history of dubious financial practices|publisher=Global News|last1=Bell|first1=Stewart|last2=Russell|first2=Andrew|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement [[memorabilia]] and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his denture clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with alcohol use and his business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFollowing the killings, the decorative signage on Wortman's denture clinic in Dartmouth, portraying a large smile and a set of dentures, garnered complaints from the public. In response, [[Halifax Regional Police]] removed the signage on April 22.<ref name=\"signage\">{{cite news |last1=April |first1=Allan |title=Police remove teeth, signage from denture clinic owned by N.S. shooter |url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/police-remove-teeth-signage-from-denture-clinic-owned-by-n-s-shooter-1.4907452 |publisher=CTV News |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigations==\n===Criminal===\nNo motive has been established for the killings, though they are not considered an act of [[terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nWortman's alleged list of targets was recovered from one of his properties. One person on the list, who was ultimately not a victim, had previously declined to sell Wortman a used police car.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citynews1130.com/2020/04/23/would-be-victim-nova-scotia-gunman-list-report/|title=Would-be victim reveals Nova Scotia gunman had 'list of people to target': report|website=CKWX|date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020|last=Gul|first=Monika}}</ref> \n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, Chief Superintendent Leather said there were 16 crime scenes, including five structure fires, over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nLeather noted that Wortman's use of a police cruiser and wearing a police uniform allowed him to help evade detection for a long time. Owning police vehicles or uniforms is not a crime, but [[Police impersonation|impersonating a police officer]] is.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Donkin|first1=Karissa|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-shooting-rcmp-vehicle-1.5539877|title=Police uniform, mock RCMP cruiser key parts of investigation into N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=[[CBC News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020|last2=Daigle|first2=Thomas}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hill|first=Brian|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6851700/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-uniform-police-car|title=How a real uniform and replica police car helped the Nova Scotia gunman go undetected|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Leather also said that Wortman had no [[Possession and acquisition licence|licence to own guns]] and that his weapons were illegally purchased, which will be investigated further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kelownanow.com/news/news/National_News/Police_have_good_idea_guns_used_in_Nova_Scotia_mass_shooting_were_not_licensed/|title=Police have 'good idea' guns used in Nova Scotia mass shooting were not licensed|website=KelownaNow|language=en|date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lamoureux|first=Mack|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/3a83av/nova-scotia-gunman-was-not-a-legal-firearms-owner-rcmp-says|title=Nova Scotia Gunman Was Not a Legal Firearms Owner, RCMP Says|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|work=Vice}}</ref>\n\nNova Scotia's [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would conduct an investigation into the shooting of Wortman, as well as another incident involving two RCMP officers who discharged their weapons inside a [[Fire station|fire hall]] in Onslow; Wortman was not there at the time.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of April 21, the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] were dispatched to assist the RCMP in their investigation by providing them with additional personnel and supplies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/military-equipment-nova-scotia-rcmp-investigation-mass-killing-1.5540743|title=Military personnel, equipment to aid RCMP investigation into mass killing|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe Nova Scotia RCMP Major Crime Unit launched a tip hotline to gather further information about the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/rcmp-launch-tip-line-to-gather-information-about-weekend-mass-shooting-1.4908807|title=RCMP launch tip line to gather information about weekend mass shooting|date=April 23, 2020|first=Leigha |last=Farnell |publisher=CTV Atlantic |language=en|access-date=April 23, 2020|last=Farnell|first=Leigha}}</ref>\n\n===Use of emergency alert===\nFollowing questions about why Nova Scotia did not use [[Alert Ready]], Canada's emergency population warning system, to warn the public about the killings and instead used popular [[social media]] platforms Twitter and [[Facebook]] to provide updates, RCMP officials said they had been dealing with an unfolding situation and details kept being updated many times. However, the areas affected had poor cellular Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not have used Twitter. Relatives of the victims pointed out that Alert Ready would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors, which could have saved lives.<ref name=\"CTV7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/u-s-citizens-in-nova-scotia-were-sent-additional-warning-during-deadly-rampage-1.4907139|title=U.S. citizens in Nova Scotia were sent additional warning during deadly rampage|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cooke|first=Alex|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-emergency-alert-1.5540220|title='I would not have let my wife leave': Widower blasts lack of emergency alert during N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/corrie-ellison-mass-shooting-brother-clinton-hiding-1.5541082|title=He was 'hunted' by the Portapique gunman and survived. His brother didn't|publisher=CBC News|last=Davie|first=Emma|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Chief Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process on alerting the public.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|last=Gorman|first=Michael|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC7\">{{cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/questions-remain-rcmp-ns-emergency-alert-1.5540100|title=Questions emerge about RCMP's failure to send emergency alert on gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, Leather said officers in Dartmouth were asked by the province about a warning at 10:15 a.m., but did not agree on details like wording before Wortman died 71 minutes later.<ref name=\"CTV6\" /> The [[List of diplomatic missions of the United States|United States Consulate]] in Halifax said it emailed American citizens in Nova Scotia warning them of the situation using the RCMP's information.<ref name=\"CTV7\"/>\n\n==Reaction==\nFlags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|work=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420223029/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing |publisher=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200421002715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]] expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening [[gun control]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He asked the media to not use Wortman's name or image: \"Do not give this person the gift of infamy.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Associated Press |url=https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|title=Canada's worst mass shooting leaves at least 18 dead|website=kktv.com|publisher=KKTV|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422085944/https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Elizabeth II]], [[monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], expressed her condolences, saying that she and [[Prince Philip]] were \"saddened by the appalling events\", and that her thoughts and prayers were with the people of Nova Scotia and all Canadians. She also paid tribute to the \"bravery and sacrifice\" of the RCMP and other emergency services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-crime-nova-scotia-britain/queen-elizabeth-sends-condolences-to-canada-after-nova-scotia-shooting-idUSKCN2231JF|title=Queen Elizabeth sends condolences to Canada after Nova Scotia shooting|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Reuters|last=Faulconbridge|first=Guy}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\"/>\n\nOn April 20, the [[CN Tower]] was illuminated in blue and white, the colours of the [[Flag of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia flag]], and also in RCMP red, blue, and gold in honour of Stevenson, on the quarter- and half-hours. On April 21, at [[Niagara Falls]], both the Canadian [[Horseshoe Falls]] and the [[American Falls]] were also illuminated in blue and white as a symbol of bi-national solidarity with Nova Scotia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/iconic-canadian-symbols-glow-blue-and-white-in-show-of-solidarity-with-nova-scotia-1.4907477|title=Iconic Canadian symbols glow blue and white in show of solidarity with Nova Scotia|publisher=CTV News|last1=Jerrett|first1=Andrea|last2=Price|first2=Melanie|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the days after the incident, many fundraisers for the victims and their families were started on the crowdfunding platform [[GoFundMe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rampage-victims-young-sons-hid-during-attack-family-member-says-1.4906956 |title=N.S. rampage victims' young sons hid during attack, family member says |publisher=[[CTV News]] |last1=Neustaeter |first1=Brooklyn |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC11\"/> There was also at least one fake or fraudulent fundraiser started, which was subsequently removed. Jeff Thomson of the RCMP's Anti-Fraud Centre warned Canadians to be diligent when donating to charities related to the tragedy.<ref name=\"CBC11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/beware-of-fake-ns-shooting-charity-campaigns-rcmp-warns-1.5541570 |title=Fake N.S. shooting fundraiser leads to warning from RCMP |publisher=[[CBC News]] |last1=Colbert |first1=Yvonne |date=April 23, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs large gatherings are restricted in the province due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|coronavirus pandemic]], a public virtual vigil is scheduled to air on CBC Atlantic on April 24 at 7:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]].<ref name=\"CBC12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/virtual-vigil-facebook-22-victims-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5541093 |title=Virtual vigil honouring victims of N.S. shootings planned for Friday |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6852130/virtual-vigil-nova-scotia-shooting |title=How to watch the virtual vigil for the Nova Scotia shooting victims |publisher=[[Global News]] |last1=Goldfinger |first1=Daina |last2=Lieberman |first2=Caryn |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n* [[List of rampage killers in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=\"CBC2\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020  |publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CNN\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">\n{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref>\n<ref name=\":5\">\n{{Cite news|last1=Mercer |first1=Greg |last2=Jones |first2=Lindsay |last3=Pruden |first3=Jana |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|title=RCMP defend not sending emergency alert before Nova Scotia gunman was killed |date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423151005/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|archive-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/we-mourn-for-their-families-teacher-nurse-cancer-survivor-among-n-s-shooting-spree-victims-1.4903446 \"'We mourn for their families': Teacher, nurse, cancer survivor among N.S. shooting spree victims\"]. [[CTV News]]. April 20, 2020.\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size1       = 8\n|      label1      = Portapique\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.3972|-63.7067}}\n|  label-pos1      = left\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = [[Portapique, Nova Scotia]]\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n\n|      label2      = Wentworth\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|45.6564|-63.5493}}\n|mark-title2       = [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label3      = Debert\n|       mark3      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3       = 8\n|  label-pos3      = right\n| label-size3      = 10\n|label-color3      = black\n| mark-coord3      = {{coord|45.4197|-63.4313}}\n|mark-title3       = [[Debert, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label4      = Shubenacadie\n|       mark4      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4       = 8\n|  label-pos4      = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label5      = Enfield\n|       mark5      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size5       = 8\n|  label-pos5      = left\n| label-size5      = 10\n|label-color5      = black\n| mark-coord5      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title5       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18|10|26 p.m.}} \u2013 <br> {{end date|2020|4|19|11|26 a.m.}} [[Atlantic Daylight Time|ADT]]\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass murder]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = 23<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/portapique-shooting-memorials-april-21-1.5539894|title=22 victims confirmed dead in N.S. mass shooting|publisher=CBC News|first=Taryn|last=Grant|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| injuries         = 2<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--><ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Unknown (under investigation)\n}}\nOver a thirteen-hour period spanning April 18\u201319, 2020, a [[killing spree]] took place at various locations in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]]. Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old man, killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people and set fire to five buildings before he was intercepted and killed by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP).<ref name=\"CBC10\"/><ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=22 victims of N.S. rampage include retirees, pregnant health care worker, veteran|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest rampage in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob |publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The RCMP has yet to establish a motive.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===April 18===\nBeginning at around 10:26 p.m., several residents of the rural beachside community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], called [[9-1-1]] to report gunshots and several fires.<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=CBC News|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-new-details-timeline-nova-scotia-manhunt-1.5541561|title=RCMP give new details on timeline of manhunt for N.S. shooter|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\"/><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead in Nova Scotia shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> [[ABC News]], citing unnamed investigators, reported that the incident may have begun as a case of [[domestic violence]] at a house where Wortman was trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"ABC2\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/death-toll-nova-scotia-shooting-rampage-increases-19/story?id=70251470|title=Nova Scotia shooting may have begun as a domestic violence dispute: Investigators|publisher=ABC News|last1=Deliso|first1=Meredith|last2=Pereira|first2=Ivan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA source told [[CNN]] that Wortman burned down his own house before going to his former partner's residence, where he killed people living there and also nearby.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> When RCMP officers arrived on the scene twelve minutes later, at around 10:38 p.m., three houses on Portapique Beach Road and Orchard Beach Drive were found burning. Thirteen victims were soon located, who had reportedly been shot after fleeing the fires. One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they could not locate an armed suspect and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/nova-scotia-shooting-manhunt-details-1.5542025|title='They don't know if they've caught him': Recordings reveal chaos of Nova Scotia manhunt|publisher=CBC News|last=Gatehouse|first=Jonathon|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":5\"/>\n\nConfusion persisted for hours over whether a suspect had been apprehended.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> At 11:32 p.m., the RCMP posted a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked and officers set up a search perimeter in the Portapique area. As the investigation developed overnight, they determined that the suspect had eluded them.<ref name=\":4\" /> By the morning of April 19, they said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=MassLive}}</ref>\n\n===April 19===\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported an explosion and gunfire at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Gabriel Wortman as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was impersonating a police officer by wearing an RCMP uniform and driving a replica police vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was seen in or near the communities of [[Glenholme, Nova Scotia|Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Onslow, Nova Scotia|Onslow]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating that he was travelling toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-timeline-of-nova-scotia-mass-shooting/|title=Timeline of Nova Scotia mass shooting|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> At 10:54 a.m., surveillance video apparently captured Wortman pulling into a parking lot in [[Millbrook 27|Millbrook First Nation]] in the mock police vehicle, briefly getting out to put on a reflective vest, and then driving off.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boynton|first=Sean|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6855907/nova-scotia-mass-shooting-new-video/|title=Video appears to show Nova Scotia shooting suspect stop, change clothes amid killing spree|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=Global News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> During this time, Wortman performed three [[Traffic stop|traffic stops]] on random cars and killed their occupants.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nAt approximately 11:15 a.m., RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson encountered Wortman oncoming on [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Route 2]] in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]], and rammed her cruiser into his replica to stop it.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/20/nova-scotia-shooting-details-emerge-in-gabriel-wortmans-rampage/|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Details emerge in suspect Gabriel Wortman's rampage|last=Sheehy|first=Kate|date=April 20, 2020|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|archive-date=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Witnesses reported that Wortman exited his vehicle and shot into Stevenson's, killing her and injuring another officer.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> Both cars also caught fire, though accounts differ as to when and how.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> Wortman then stole a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] from a nearby motorist, and was next seen continuing south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] through [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]] at 11:24 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThirteen hours after police began pursuing him, at 11:26 a.m., Wortman was finally intercepted, shot, and killed by at least one officer at the [[Irving Oil#Big Stops|Irving Big Stop]] [[Rest area|service area]] in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> His death was confirmed by police at 11:40 a.m.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people, including Constable Heidi Stevenson. He shot another officer, who survived.<ref name=\"CBC10\" /><ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> One other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> Victims were found in the communities of Portapique, Wentworth, Debert, Shubenacadie/Milford and Enfield.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|title=Canada shooting: Death toll in Nova Scotia rises to 22|publisher=BBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422000411/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nAccording to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of Wortman's first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, those he attacked became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' reported that Wortman had created a list of people to target, although not all those on the list were attacked. The newspaper noted that the two victims at the home in Wentworth were known to Wortman because one had previously gone hunting with him.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Perpetrator==\n [[File:Atlantic Denture Clinic (3).jpg|thumb|Workers removing signage from the perpetrator's denture clinic in Dartmouth on April 22]]\n\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer, his [[yearbook]] entry alluding to this.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020|last=Frisko|first=Bruce}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a polite and [[Wiktionary:house-proud#English|house-proud]] man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman pleaded guilty to assault in 2002 and was sentenced to nine months of probation, in which he was prohibited from possessing weapons and ordered to undergo anger management counselling.<ref name=\"CTV6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rcmp-say-they-were-in-process-of-preparing-alert-when-gunman-was-killed-1.4906672|title=N.S. RCMP say they were 'in process' of preparing alert when gunman was killed|publisher=CTV News|last=Flanagan|first=Ryan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC8\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-criminal-record-1.5541176|title=Suspect in N.S. killings didn't have criminal record, but previously pleaded guilty to a crime|publisher=CBC News|last=Donkin|first=Karissa|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> He was also involved in two civil matters regarding property disputes, according to interviews and public records. A former acquaintance described how, in 2004, Wortman offered to help him when he had financial difficulties and was about to lose his house, only for Wortman to discreetly take ownership of the home away from him, evict him, and sell the property. In 2015, Wortman had been temporarily loaned a Portapique home a paternal uncle had purchased while he was in the process of selling his [[Edmonton]] condominium. Wortman refused to release the Portapique property back to him, claiming he was owed money, until the uncle eventually sold it.<ref name=\"CBC8\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6846920/nova-scotia-killer-financial-practices/|title='He stole my house': Nova Scotia killer had history of dubious financial practices|publisher=Global News|last1=Bell|first1=Stewart|last2=Russell|first2=Andrew|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement [[memorabilia]] and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his denture clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with alcohol use and his business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFollowing the killings, the decorative signage on Wortman's denture clinic in Dartmouth, portraying a large smile and a set of dentures, garnered complaints from the public. In response, [[Halifax Regional Police]] removed the signage on April 22.<ref name=\"signage\">{{cite news |last1=April |first1=Allan |title=Police remove teeth, signage from denture clinic owned by N.S. shooter |url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/police-remove-teeth-signage-from-denture-clinic-owned-by-n-s-shooter-1.4907452 |publisher=CTV News |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigations==\n===Criminal===\nNo motive has been established for the killings, though they are not considered an act of [[terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nWortman's alleged list of targets was recovered from one of his properties. One person on the list, who was ultimately not a victim, had previously declined to sell Wortman a used police car.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citynews1130.com/2020/04/23/would-be-victim-nova-scotia-gunman-list-report/|title=Would-be victim reveals Nova Scotia gunman had 'list of people to target': report|website=CKWX|date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020|last=Gul|first=Monika}}</ref> \n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, Chief Superintendent Leather said there were 16 crime scenes, including five structure fires, over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nLeather noted that Wortman's use of a police cruiser and wearing a police uniform allowed him to help evade detection for a long time. Owning police vehicles or uniforms is not a crime, but [[Police impersonation|impersonating a police officer]] is.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Donkin|first1=Karissa|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-shooting-rcmp-vehicle-1.5539877|title=Police uniform, mock RCMP cruiser key parts of investigation into N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=[[CBC News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020|last2=Daigle|first2=Thomas}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hill|first=Brian|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6851700/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-uniform-police-car|title=How a real uniform and replica police car helped the Nova Scotia gunman go undetected|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Leather also said that Wortman had no [[Possession and acquisition licence|licence to own guns]] and that his weapons were illegally purchased, which will be investigated further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kelownanow.com/news/news/National_News/Police_have_good_idea_guns_used_in_Nova_Scotia_mass_shooting_were_not_licensed/|title=Police have 'good idea' guns used in Nova Scotia mass shooting were not licensed|website=KelownaNow|language=en|date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lamoureux|first=Mack|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/3a83av/nova-scotia-gunman-was-not-a-legal-firearms-owner-rcmp-says|title=Nova Scotia Gunman Was Not a Legal Firearms Owner, RCMP Says|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|work=Vice}}</ref>\n\nNova Scotia's [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would conduct an investigation into the shooting of Wortman, as well as another incident involving two RCMP officers who discharged their weapons inside a [[Fire station|fire hall]] in Onslow; Wortman was not there at the time.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of April 21, the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] were dispatched to assist the RCMP in their investigation by providing them with additional personnel and supplies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/military-equipment-nova-scotia-rcmp-investigation-mass-killing-1.5540743|title=Military personnel, equipment to aid RCMP investigation into mass killing|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe Nova Scotia RCMP Major Crime Unit launched a tip hotline to gather further information about the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/rcmp-launch-tip-line-to-gather-information-about-weekend-mass-shooting-1.4908807|title=RCMP launch tip line to gather information about weekend mass shooting|date=April 23, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 23, 2020|last=Farnell|first=Leigha}}</ref>\n\n===Use of emergency alert===\nFollowing questions about why Nova Scotia did not use [[Alert Ready]], Canada's emergency population warning system, to warn the public about the killings and instead used popular [[social media]] platforms Twitter and [[Facebook]] to provide updates, RCMP officials said they had been dealing with an unfolding situation and details kept being updated many times. However, the areas affected had poor cellular Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not have used Twitter. Relatives of the victims pointed out that Alert Ready would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors, which could have saved lives.<ref name=\"CTV7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/u-s-citizens-in-nova-scotia-were-sent-additional-warning-during-deadly-rampage-1.4907139|title=U.S. citizens in Nova Scotia were sent additional warning during deadly rampage|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cooke|first=Alex|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-emergency-alert-1.5540220|title='I would not have let my wife leave': Widower blasts lack of emergency alert during N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/corrie-ellison-mass-shooting-brother-clinton-hiding-1.5541082|title=He was 'hunted' by the Portapique gunman and survived. His brother didn't|publisher=CBC News|last=Davie|first=Emma|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Chief Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process on alerting the public.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|last=Gorman|first=Michael|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC7\">{{cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/questions-remain-rcmp-ns-emergency-alert-1.5540100|title=Questions emerge about RCMP's failure to send emergency alert on gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, Leather said officers in Dartmouth were asked by the province about a warning at 10:15 a.m., but did not agree on details like wording before Wortman died 71 minutes later.<ref name=\"CTV6\" /> The [[List of diplomatic missions of the United States|United States Consulate]] in Halifax said it emailed American citizens in Nova Scotia warning them of the situation using the RCMP's information.<ref name=\"CTV7\"/>\n\n==Reaction==\nFlags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|work=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420223029/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing |publisher=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200421002715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]] expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening [[gun control]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He asked the media to not use Wortman's name or image: \"Do not give this person the gift of infamy.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Associated Press |url=https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|title=Canada's worst mass shooting leaves at least 18 dead|website=kktv.com|publisher=KKTV|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422085944/https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Elizabeth II]], [[monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], expressed her condolences, saying that she and [[Prince Philip]] were \"saddened by the appalling events\", and that her thoughts and prayers were with the people of Nova Scotia and all Canadians. She also paid tribute to the \"bravery and sacrifice\" of the RCMP and other emergency services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-crime-nova-scotia-britain/queen-elizabeth-sends-condolences-to-canada-after-nova-scotia-shooting-idUSKCN2231JF|title=Queen Elizabeth sends condolences to Canada after Nova Scotia shooting|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Reuters|last=Faulconbridge|first=Guy}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\"/>\n\nOn April 20, the [[CN Tower]] was illuminated in blue and white, the colours of the [[Flag of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia flag]], and also in RCMP red, blue, and gold in honour of Stevenson, on the quarter- and half-hours. On April 21, at [[Niagara Falls]], both the Canadian [[Horseshoe Falls]] and the [[American Falls]] were also illuminated in blue and white as a symbol of bi-national solidarity with Nova Scotia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/iconic-canadian-symbols-glow-blue-and-white-in-show-of-solidarity-with-nova-scotia-1.4907477|title=Iconic Canadian symbols glow blue and white in show of solidarity with Nova Scotia|publisher=CTV News|last1=Jerrett|first1=Andrea|last2=Price|first2=Melanie|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the days after the incident, many fundraisers for the victims and their families were started on the crowdfunding platform [[GoFundMe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rampage-victims-young-sons-hid-during-attack-family-member-says-1.4906956 |title=N.S. rampage victims' young sons hid during attack, family member says |publisher=[[CTV News]] |last1=Neustaeter |first1=Brooklyn |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC11\"/> There was also at least one fake or fraudulent fundraiser started, which was subsequently removed. Jeff Thomson of the RCMP's Anti-Fraud Centre warned Canadians to be diligent when donating to charities related to the tragedy.<ref name=\"CBC11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/beware-of-fake-ns-shooting-charity-campaigns-rcmp-warns-1.5541570 |title=Fake N.S. shooting fundraiser leads to warning from RCMP |publisher=[[CBC News]] |last1=Colbert |first1=Yvonne |date=April 23, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs large gatherings are restricted in the province due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|coronavirus pandemic]], a public virtual vigil is scheduled to air on CBC Atlantic on April 24 at 7:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]].<ref name=\"CBC12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/virtual-vigil-facebook-22-victims-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5541093 |title=Virtual vigil honouring victims of N.S. shootings planned for Friday |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6852130/virtual-vigil-nova-scotia-shooting |title=How to watch the virtual vigil for the Nova Scotia shooting victims |publisher=[[Global News]] |last1=Goldfinger |first1=Daina |last2=Lieberman |first2=Caryn |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n* [[List of rampage killers in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=\"CBC2\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020  |publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CNN\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">\n{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref>\n<ref name=\":5\">\n{{Cite news|last1=Mercer |first1=Greg |last2=Jones |first2=Lindsay |last3=Pruden |first3=Jana |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|title=RCMP defend not sending emergency alert before Nova Scotia gunman was killed |date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423151005/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|archive-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/we-mourn-for-their-families-teacher-nurse-cancer-survivor-among-n-s-shooting-spree-victims-1.4903446 \"'We mourn for their families': Teacher, nurse, cancer survivor among N.S. shooting spree victims\"]. [[CTV News]]. April 20, 2020.\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCriminal:author in cite", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "2014 South Napa earthquake", "text_new": "{{short description|Earthquake in California in 2014}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox earthquake\n|title = 2014 South Napa earthquake\n|timestamp = 2014-08-24 10:20:44\n|anss-url = nc72282711\n|isc-event = 610572079\n|image = 2014 South Napa quake - Stones Fallen From Face of Sam Kee - 1 (15014707736).jpg\n|image alt =\n|caption = Damage to the [[Sam Kee Laundry Building]]\n|map =\n|map alt = The earthquake's epicenter is shown in California.\n|image name =\n| map2 = {{Location map+ | USA California\n | relief = yes\n | places =\n{{Location map~|California|lat=38.22|long=-122.31|mark=Bullseye1.svg|marksize=40}}\n{{Location map~|California|lat=38.3|long=-122.3|label=Napa|label_size=100|mark=Green pog.svg}}\n | width = 260\n | float = right\n | caption = }}\n|local-date = {{Start date|2014|8|24}}\n|local-time = 03:20:44 PDT (UTC-7)\n|duration =\n|magnitude = 6.0 [[Moment magnitude scale|M<sub>w</sub>]]<ref name=usgs />\n|depth = {{convert|7|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=usgs />\n|location = {{Coord|38.22|N|122.31|W|display=title, inline}}<ref name=usgs />\n|fault = [[West Napa Fault]]\n|type = [[Fault (geology)#Strike-slip faults|Strike-slip]]<ref name=usgs />\n|countries affected = {{nowrap|[[North Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)]]}} <br> [[California]], United States\n|damage = $362 million\u2013$1 billion<ref name=\"362 million\"/><ref name=latimeseconomic/>\n|intensity = [[Mercalli intensity scale|VIII (''Severe'')]]<ref name=usgs />\n|landslide =\n|aftershocks =\n|casualties = 1 killed<ref>{{citation|title=Powerful California earthquake now blamed for one death|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/09/10/us/california-earthquake-death-toll/|first=Josh|last=Levs|date=September 11, 2014|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref><br>about 200 injured<ref name=\"PD-NPB\"/>\n}}\nThe '''2014 South Napa earthquake''' occurred in the [[North Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)|North San Francisco Bay Area]] on August 24 at {{tooltip|03:20:44 Pacific Daylight Time|10:20:44 UTC}}. At 6.0 on the [[moment magnitude scale]] and with a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale|Mercalli intensity]] of VIII (''Severe''), the event was the largest in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] since the [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake]]. The epicenter of the earthquake was located to the south of [[Napa, California|Napa]] and to the northwest of [[American Canyon, California|American Canyon]] on the [[West Napa Fault]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://m.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Boats-grapes-and-Poseidon-at-Napa-quake-s-5714272.php|title = Boats, grapes and Poseidon at Napa quake's epicenter|last = Fimrite|first = Peter|date = August 27, 2014|work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate = 2 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nTotal damage in the southern [[Napa County, California|Napa Valley]] and [[Vallejo, California|Vallejo]] areas was in the range of $362 million to $1 billion, with one person killed and 200 injured. Other aspects of the event included an experimental [[earthquake warning system]] that alerted seismologists several seconds before the damaging [[S-wave|shear waves]] arrived, temporary changes in springs and wells, and the potential for [[wikt:postseismic|postseismic]] [[aseismic creep|fault creep]].\n\n==Tectonic setting==\n{{see also|California earthquake forecast|Strike-slip tectonics}}\n\nThe [[San Andreas Fault|San Andreas Fault System]] is an active plate boundary comprising [[Sinistral and dextral#Geology|right-lateral]] [[Fault (geology)#Strike-slip faults|strike-slip]] faults that runs nearly the length of California. This network of faults trends north-northwest in the area of the [[West Napa Fault]], where it is {{convert|80|km|order=flip}} wide from west to east. The West Napa Fault transfers slip between a group of related faults (including the [[Concord Fault]] and the [[Calaveras Fault]]) called the Contra Costa Shear Zone, which was assigned a maximum slip rate of 1mm/yr in the third Uniform California Earthquake Rupture Forecast. The authors of a separate study that focused on [[Global Positioning System]] data gave an estimated slip rate of 4\u00b13mm/yr for the West Napa Fault.<ref name=Brocher>{{citation|title=The Mw 6.0 24 August 2014 South Napa Earthquake |url=https://seismo.berkeley.edu/~rallen/pub/2015brocher/BrocherEtAl-SRL-2015.pdf|first=T. M.|last=Brocher|first2=A. S.|last2=Baltay|first3=J. L.|last3=Hardebeck|authorlink3=Jeanne L. Hardebeck|first4=F. F.|last4=Pollitz|first5=J. R.|last5=Murray|first6=A. L.|last6=Llenos|first7=D. P.|last7=Schwartz|first8=J. L.|last8=Blair|first9=D. J.|last9=Ponti|first10=J. J.|last10=Lienkaemper|first11=V. E.|last11=Langenheim|first12=T. E.|last12=Dawson|first13=K. W.|last13=Hudnut|first14=D. R.|last14=Shelly|first15=D. S.|last15=Dreger|first16=J.|last16=Boatright|first17=B. T|last17=Aagaard|first18=D. J.|last18=Wald|first19=R. M.|last19=Allen|first20=W. D.|last20=Barnhart|first21=K. L.|last21=Knudsen|first22=B. A.|last22=Brooks|first23=K. M.|last23=Scharer|year=2015|journal=Seismological Research Letters|volume=86|number=2A|page=309|doi=10.1785/0220150004 }}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Active Faults of the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aQUgAwAAQBAJ|last=Yeats|first=R.|date=2012|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0521190855|pages=82, 83}}</ref>\n\n==Earthquake==\nThe mainshock was magnitude 6.0, with a depth of 11.3&nbsp;km.<ref name=usgs /> The [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS) estimated that 15,000 people experienced severe shaking, 106,000 people felt very strong shaking, 176,000 felt strong shaking, and 738,000 felt moderate shaking.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> The earthquake lasted 10 to 20 seconds, depending on location.<ref name=\"latimes.lanow\" /> At least twelve aftershocks followed, including one of magnitude 3.9.<ref name=\"aftersh\">{{Cite news|last = Rossmann|first = Randi|title = 3.9M aftershock rattles Napa|journal = [[The Press Democrat]]|location = Santa Rosa|date = August 26, 2014|url = http://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/2591205-181/napa-rattled-by-39m-aftershock|accessdate = 2014-08-27|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140903085339/http://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/2591205-181/napa-rattled-by-39m-aftershock|archive-date = September 3, 2014|url-status = dead|df = mdy-all}}</ref>  The earthquake was the largest earthquake in the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]] since the magnitude 6.9 [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake]].<ref name=\"latimes.lanow\">{{cite news |title=After earthquake near Napa, up to 100 homes labeled unfit to enter|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-quake-near-napa-jolts-bay-area-20140824-story.html |author=Lee Romney |author2=Ryan Parker |author3=Christine Mai-Duc |author4=Lauren Raab|accessdate=August 25, 2014 |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 24, 2014}}</ref> Governor [[Jerry Brown]] declared a [[State of emergency#United States|state of emergency]] due to the severe damage and the possibility of aftershocks.<ref name=\"wsj 14:23 ET\">{{cite news|title=Strong Earthquake Shakes Northern California|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/6-0-earthquake-shakes-northern-california-1408882575|accessdate=August 24, 2014|publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=August 24, 2014}}</ref> [[President Obama]] declared a major disaster for Napa and Solano counties.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Napa-quake-Obama-declares-major-disaster-5749556.php|title = Napa quake: Obama declares major disaster, freeing up aid|last = Williams|first = Kate|date = September 15, 2014|work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate = 2 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Damage===\n\nSeveral older commercial buildings in downtown Napa showed signs of extensive external damage even though many had been retrofitted for earthquake safety protection.<ref name=cnn>{{cite news |author=Josh Levs |author2=Susanna Capelouto |author3=Joshua Berlinger |last-author-amp=yes |title= Northern California earthquake is area's strongest in 25 years |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/08/24/us/california-earthquake/ |accessdate=August 25, 2014 |work=CNN |date=August 24, 2014}}</ref> The [[Goodman Library]], [[Napa County Courthouse Plaza]], [[Sam Kee Laundry Building]], [[U.S. Post Office (Napa, California)|Downtown U.S. Post Office]], [[Alexandria Hotel and Annex]], [[Native Sons of the Golden West]] building,<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Yune| first = Howard | title = Earthquake damage repaired, Napa's Native Sons building shines again| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = March 20, 2018| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/earthquake-damage-repaired-napa-s-native-sons-building-shines-again/article_5d139ead-34e6-559d-93b0-6f60f2edda89.html#tracking-source=home-top-story| accessdate = March 21, 2018}}</ref> First United Methodist Church, and [[First Presbyterian Church (Napa, California)|First Presbyterian Church]] all suffered moderate to extensive damage.<ref name=\"PD-NPB\">{{Cite news|last1= Moore |first1= Derek |last2= Rossmann |first2= Randi |date= August 14, 2014 |title= Napa's people, buildings hit hard by 6.0 earthquake |url= http://www.pressdemocrat.com/home/2575107-181/napas-people-buildings-hit-hard |newspaper= [[The Press Democrat]]|location= Santa Rosa |accessdate= 2014-08-25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2014 South Napa eathquake Alexandria Square building.jpg|thumb|left|Damaged Alexandria Square building in Napa]]\n\nAll of these buildings are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]. Although the structure of the [[Uptown Theater (Napa, California)|Uptown Theater]] was determined to be sound, the building was [[Color-tagged structure|red-tagged]] due to damage to the theater's ceiling.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = Uptown to remain closed until November| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 11, 2014| url =http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/uptown-to-remain-closed-until-november/article_a75ae773-4591-5db2-bbae-1ed7f0813481.html| accessdate = September 11, 2014}}</ref>  Several newer commercial buildings also suffered damage.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = Damaged businesses struggle to reopen| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = August 25, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/damaged-businesses-struggle-to-reopen/article_a5f0c5ab-1c09-5a4d-8cd0-26e3d09ddf6b.html| accessdate = August 26, 2014}}</ref>  Six major fires broke out,<ref name=\"cnn\" /> and four homes in Napa Valley Mobile Home Park located in north Napa were destroyed.  Firefighters were hampered in their efforts to fight this fire by a broken water main.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Wetzstein| first = Janelle | title = Shattered property, bruised lives| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = August 24, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/shattered-property-bruised-lives/article_1af7d38c-2d23-532d-a9da-b2c5c9e3def4.html| accessdate = August 26, 2014}}</ref> In Vallejo, several hundred storefront windows shattered and many building walls suffered extensive damage. A water main on [[Mare Island]] broke.<ref name=fimritevallejo>Fimrite, Peter. [http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Northern-California-earthquake-Blue-collar-5711775.php Northern California earthquake: Blue-collar Vallejo hit hard], ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', August 26, 2014.</ref>\n\nFollowing the first round of building inspections by the City of Napa inspectors, a total of 613 structures had been tagged; 113 were red-tagged and 500 had been yellow-tagged.<ref>{{Cite journal| last =  Polson| first = Burt| title = A red-tagged building and a tenant| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 1, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/business/columnists/burt-polson/a-red-tagged-building-and-a-tenant/article_f8a06146-85fb-5bca-bacf-8dae22c9f357.html| accessdate = September 11, 2014}}</ref> Pavement on several roads in [[Napa County|Napa]], [[Solano County|Solano]] and [[Sonoma County|Sonoma]] Counties buckled and cracked during the quake.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Cabanatuan| first = Michael| title = Earthquake cracks, buckles roads, but leaves bridges OK| journal = [[SF Gate]]| location = Napa, CA| date = August 24, 2014| url = http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Quake-buckles-cracks-roads-but-leaves-bridges-5709018.php| accessdate = August 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWithin days, County officials estimated the damage at $362 million.<ref name=\"362 million\">{{Cite news|last = Carter|first = Lori|title = Napa quake damage rises to $362 million |journal = [[The Press Democrat]]|location = Santa Rosa|date = August 28, 2014|url = http://www.pressdemocrat.com/home/2613337-181/napa-quake-damage-rises-to|accessdate = 2014-08-28 }}</ref>  According to an early estimate by the USGS, the economic costs to Napa County may go as high as $1 billion.<ref name=latimeseconomic>Stevens, Matt. [http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-napa-earthquake-damage-cost-20140825-story.html Napa, Calif., earthquake: Economic hit could reach $1 billion], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', August 25, 2014.</ref> Several wineries including Hess Collection and [[Trefethen Vineyards]] suffered damage to buildings and infrastructure.  Several wine storage facilities also suffered damage and loss of property.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Paulsen| first = Sasha| title = Wine industry tallies spilled wine, shattered barrels| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = August 25, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/wine-industry-tallies-spilled-wine-shattered-barrels/article_bb75cbb0-dab2-5211-ad1c-fafd5367e854.html| accessdate = August 25, 2014}}</ref>  Estimates of the damage to the wine industry were downgraded to between $80 and $100 million in a September 5, 2014 report from [[Silicon Valley Bank]] to the Napa County Board of Supervisors.<ref>{{Cite journal| last =  Jensen| first = Peter| title = Napa quakes causes $80 million blow to wine industry, report says| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 9, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/napa-quakes-causes-million-blow-to-wine-industry-report-says/article_dc263bc9-41a8-5282-adf4-adafc8d04181.html| accessdate = September 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, 2014 in a report to the Napa City Council, members were briefed on the status of damage sustained.  City Staff reported that 156 commercial and residential structures had been red-tagged and 1398 had been yellow-tagged.  It was also reported that the estimate for damage to the City's infrastructure had reached $57.9 million.  This total included repairs made to 144 water mains, repairs or replacement of a compromised water tank in Brown's Valley that is part of the City's water system and repair of 294 locations where streets and sidewalks had been damaged.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Ynue| first = Howard| title = Napa tallies earthquake damage across city| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 17, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/napa-tallies-earthquake-damage-across-city/article_82e2905c-4b2d-545c-a856-180e668a8613.html| accessdate = September 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shake Intensity - 2014 South Napa Earthquake.jpg|thumb|USGS ShakeMap for the event]]\n\n===Injuries===\nAbout 200 injured people were treated at [[Queen of the Valley Medical Center (Napa, California)|Queen of the Valley Medical Center]] in Napa.<ref name=\"PD-NPB\"/> Thirteen of those injured were admitted. Nicholas Dillon was gravely injured after many bricks from a chimney fell on him.<ref name=\"kgo7 4:45 PDT\" /> Many of the injuries were lacerations and abrasions from fallen debris.<ref name=\"cnn\" /> At least six of the injuries were classified as critical.<ref name=\"kgo7 4:45 PDT\">[[KGO-TV]] report from Queen of the Valley Medical Center, 4:45 pm</ref> In Vallejo, 49 people were injured, including two who were hospitalized.<ref name=fimritevallejo/> CNN reported one individual still in critical condition, later discovery determined as a 58-year-old male who went through two surgeries, awakening four days later in ICU to discover it was going to take him approximately two years to learn how to walk again. One person died September 5 as a result of injuries from the quake.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-napa-woman-dies-napa-earthquake-toppled-tv-20140910-story.html |title=Napa earthquake death: 2 weeks later, quake claims first victim -|journal=LA Times |author= Rong-Gong Lin II|website= |accessdate=2014-09-10|date=September 10, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last =  Todorov| first = Kerana| title = First earthquake-related death reported| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 9, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/first-earthquake-related-death-reported/article_df5e8346-0239-5651-916a-ec5f991aae51.html#| accessdate = September 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Recovery===\nSeveral of the historic buildings damaged in the earthquake have been repaired while others are still awaiting renovation and restoration.  The Uptown Theater was the first to reopen on November 9, 2014.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Yune| first = Howard| title = Crumbled by Napa earthquake, Uptown Theatre mural rises again| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = November 17, 2014| url =http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/crumbled-by-napa-earthquake-uptown-theatre-mural-rises-again/article_0208cd23-bb5b-5001-bdd9-891811fcc7bc.html| accessdate = November 17, 2014}}</ref>  The congregation of the First Presbyterian Church moved back into the sanctuary in July 2016 following repairs and restoration at a cost of $850,000.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = First Presbyterian church returns to quake-damaged sanctuary after almost two years| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = July 9, 2016| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/first-presbyterian-church-returns-to-quake-damaged-sanctuary-after-almost/article_1ae0b8d3-db2c-5dcd-9c65-dd702ff5b990.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> The United Methodist Church received $2.2 million in repairs and upgrades and reopened the doors to its congregation in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = Churches repair and reopen after quake| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = August 23, 2015| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/churches-repair-and-reopen-after-quake/article_7c94b89e-7e81-57c1-8993-d407b853355b.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Yune| first = Howard| title = After earthquake repairs, Napa Methodist church to reopen Sunday| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = November 17, 2015| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/after-earthquake-repairs-napa-methodist-church-to-reopen-sunday/article_7e23295c-1a88-53dc-83ab-1c6fb3ec25a7.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> A $1.75 million contract to repair damage to the Goodman Library was awarded in January 2017 and work on the building is expected to be completed in early 2018.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Yune| first = Howard| title = Napa awards repair contract for quake-damaged Goodman Library| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = January 25, 2017| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/eagle/news/local/napa-awards-repair-contract-for-quake-damaged-goodman-library/article_9fcd7f88-f5a2-5cf4-a168-3410100c6f0c.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service]] determined that repairing the building would be too costly and sold it to a developer for $2 million.  The developer plans to turn the building into a hotel.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = Napa's old post office sold for $2 million for a hotel| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = March 10, 2017| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/damaged-businesses-struggle-to-reopen/article_a5f0c5ab-1c09-5a4d-8cd0-26e3d09ddf6b.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> An $11.6 million contract for restoration of the courthouse was awarded by [[Napa County]] in August 2017.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Eberling| first = Barry| title = Repair of earthquake damage to Napa courthouse to start soon| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 1, 2017| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/repair-of-earthquake-damage-to-napa-courthouse-to-start-soon/article_3d5af16a-47b7-51bb-8da2-f79f9cf1e0cc.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> The heavily damaged Trefethen Vineyard Eschol building was restored from earthquake damage following over two years of repairs and improvements.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Lander| first = Jess|title = Trefethen rebounds after the earthquake |journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = March 30, 2017| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/wine/trefethen-rebounds-after-the-earthquake/article_979ac4fb-dfa7-535e-904a-2a1c3ab640f3.html| accessdate = April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hydrologic effects===\nThe event was credited with large, temporary increases in the water flow of several nearby streams, including [[Carriger Creek (Sonoma County, California)|Carriger Creek]], Calabasas Creek, Felder Creek, [[Sonoma Creek]], Tulocay Creek, Green Valley Creek, and Wild Horse Creek.  In addition, the water levels of several wells in the [[Sonoma Valley]] rose suddenly at the time of the quake, in one instance by {{Convert|5|feet}}.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Napa quake jumpstarts stream flows, though probably only temporarily |date=September 4, 2014 |url=http://www.pressdemocrat.com/home/2655382-181/napa-quake-jumpstarts-stream-flows|last=Kovner|first=Guy|accessdate=September 4, 2014|work=[[The Press Democrat]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.sfgate.com/science/article/Surprise-bonanza-since-Napa-quake-dry-creeks-now-5739098.php|title = Surprise bonanza since Napa quake: dry creeks now flowing|last = Fimrite|first = Peter|date = September 6, 2014|work = San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate = 7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Fault creep===\n{{Further|Aseismic creep}}\n\nIn the following months, geologists studying the effects of the event warned that a potential afterslip could cause the previously unmapped portion of the fault in the Browns Valley area of Napa to slowly move up to another {{convert|6|in|mm}} in the next 3 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-quake-napa-fault-20141217-story.html |title=After big quake, Napa fault could move 6 inches in 3 years |journal=LA Times |date=December 17, 2014 |author= Rong-Gong Lin II |author2= Rosanna Xia |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-quake-napa-fault-20141226-story.html#page=1 |title=Napa's surprise fault line triggers earthquake study of the region |journal=LA Times |date=December 26, 2014 |author= Rong-Gong Lin II |author2= Rosanna Xia |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==Earthquake warning==\n{{Main|ShakeAlert}}\nAn experimental [[earthquake warning system]] being developed by the [[Berkeley Seismological Laboratory]] issued a warning upon detecting the [[P-wave]]s five seconds before the slower, more destructive [[S-wave]]s arrived in Berkeley. Initially this was reported to be a 10-second warning in Berkeley,<ref name=cbs>{{cite news|title=Experimental warning system gave 10-second alert before California earthquake |work=[[CBS News]] |date=August 24, 2014 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/experimental-warning-system-gave-10-second-alert-before-quake-hit/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6S5x6f9mE?url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/experimental-warning-system-gave-10-second-alert-before-quake-hit/ |archivedate=August 25, 2014 |url-status=live|df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = In Latest Calif. Earthquake, Shake Alert Tests Its Legs|url = https://www.npr.org/2014/08/25/343203813/in-latest-calif-earthquake-shake-alert-tests-its-legs|website = NPR|accessdate = 2015-08-23|first = Melissa|last = Block}}</ref> but revised information indicates only a 5-second warning was provided.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Allen|first1=Richard M.|last2=Given|first2=Douglas D.|last3=Heaton|first3=Thomas H.|authorlink3=Thomas H. Heaton|last4=Vidale|first4=John E.|authorlink4=John Vidale|title=Successful ShakeAlert Performance for the Napa Quake|journal=2014 AGU Fall Meeting|volume=44|date=2014|issue=S44D\u201301|pages=S44D\u201301|bibcode=2014AGUFM.S44D..01A}}</ref> This means the S-waves had already arrived in Napa and Vallejo when the warning was issued.\n\nSeismic Warning Systems, Inc., a private earthquake warning company based in [[Scotts Valley, California|Scotts Valley, CA]], had installed on-site warning systems at five fire stations in Vallejo in 2002 and 2003.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wurman|first1=Gilead|last2=Price|first2=Michael J.|title=Earthquake Warning Performance in Vallejo for the South Napa Quake|journal=2014 AGU Fall Meeting|date=2014|issue=S33F\u20134937|location=San Francisco, CA}}</ref> These systems commanded the bay doors to open at these fire stations between 1.7 and 2.4 seconds before the S-waves arrived at each fire station.\n\nEarthquake warning systems could potentially give people time to take cover in the event of a quake, preventing injuries caused by falling debris, automatically stopping trains or shutting off gas lines. The system being developed at the Berkeley Seismological Laboratory (called [[ShakeAlert]]) in conjunction with the [[United States Geological Survey]], the [[California Institute of Technology]] and the [[University of Washington]], will eventually cover the entire West Coast. The system would cost $80 million in funding to run for five years in California, or $120 million for the whole West Coast.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/early-warning-system-in-testing-sounded-alarm-before-quake-1408999597|title = Expanding Earthquake Warning System May Help the Public|last = Elinson|first = Zusha|date = 25 August 2014|work = Wall Street Journal|accessdate = 26 August 2014}}</ref> In December 2014, [[United States Congress]] approved a $5 million allocation as part of the [[Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2014]] in order to expand funding for development of the system.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-quake-early-warning-20141215-story.html |title=California receives U.S. funding for earthquake early-warning system- LA Times |date=December 14, 2014 |author= Rong-Gong Lin II|work= |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n* [[List of earthquakes in 2014]]\n* [[List of earthquakes in California]]\n* [[List of earthquakes in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|32em|refs=\n<ref name=usgs>{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/nc72282711#summary|title=M6.0 \u2013 6km NW of American Canyon, California|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|author=USGS}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|24 August 2014 earthquake centered in Napa, California, USA}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jddUOtyz9zk SCEC's Response to the South Napa Earthquake] \u2013 [[Southern California Earthquake Center]]\n* [https://www.llnl.gov/sites/default/files/field/file/South_Napa_slides.pdf The August 24, 2014 South Napa Earthquake: What Is Known So Far, Accessing Open Information And Preliminary Ground Motion Simulations] \u2013 [[Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory]]\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28918600 California earthquake strikes San Francisco Bay area] \u2013 ''[[BBC News]]''\n* [https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/08/24/us-usaearthquake-idUSKBN0GO0A520140824 Quake rocks California wine country, dozens injured] \u2013 [[Reuters]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140826113933/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/research/external/reports/05HQAG0002.pdf Mapping of the West Napa Fault Zone for input into the Northern California Quaternary fault database]\n* {{EQ-isc-link|610572079}}\n* [http://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/8433959-181/study-2014-napa-quake-may Study: 2014 Napa quake may be linked to groundwater changes]\n\n{{Earthquakes in 2014}}\n{{Earthquakes in California}}\n{{Earthquakes in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:South Napa Earthquake, 2014}}\n[[Category:2014 earthquakes]]\n[[Category:2014 in California]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in California|2014]]\n[[Category:Geology of Napa County, California]]\n[[Category:History of Napa County, California]]\n[[Category:History of Solano County, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox earthquake\n|title = 2014 South Napa earthquake\n|timestamp = 2014-08-24 10:20:44\n|anss-url = nc72282711\n|isc-event = 610572079\n|image = 2014 South Napa quake - Stones Fallen From Face of Sam Kee - 1 (15014707736).jpg\n|image alt =\n|caption = Damage to the [[Sam Kee Laundry Building]]\n|map =\n|map alt = The earthquake's epicenter is shown in California.\n|image name =\n| map2 = {{Location map+ | USA California\n | relief = yes\n | places =\n{{Location map~|California|lat=38.22|long=-122.31|mark=Bullseye1.svg|marksize=40}}\n{{Location map~|California|lat=38.3|long=-122.3|label=Napa|label_size=100|mark=Green pog.svg}}\n | width = 260\n | float = right\n | caption = }}\n|local-date = {{Start date|2014|8|24}}\n|local-time = 03:20:44 PDT (UTC-7)\n|duration =\n|magnitude = 6.0 [[Moment magnitude scale|M<sub>w</sub>]]<ref name=usgs />\n|depth = {{convert|7|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=usgs />\n|location = {{Coord|38.22|N|122.31|W|display=title, inline}}<ref name=usgs />\n|fault = [[West Napa Fault]]\n|type = [[Fault (geology)#Strike-slip faults|Strike-slip]]<ref name=usgs />\n|countries affected = {{nowrap|[[North Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)]]}} <br> [[California]], United States\n|damage = $362 million\u2013$1 billion<ref name=\"362 million\"/><ref name=latimeseconomic/>\n|intensity = [[Mercalli intensity scale|VIII (''Severe'')]]<ref name=usgs />\n|landslide =\n|aftershocks =\n|casualties = 1 killed<ref>{{citation|title=Powerful California earthquake now blamed for one death|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/09/10/us/california-earthquake-death-toll/|first=Josh|last=Levs|date=September 11, 2014|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref><br>about 200 injured<ref name=\"PD-NPB\"/>\n}}\nThe '''2014 South Napa earthquake''' occurred in the [[North Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)|North San Francisco Bay Area]] on August 24 at {{tooltip|03:20:44 Pacific Daylight Time|10:20:44 UTC}}. At 6.0 on the [[moment magnitude scale]] and with a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale|Mercalli intensity]] of VIII (''Severe''), the event was the largest in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] since the [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake]]. The epicenter of the earthquake was located to the south of [[Napa, California|Napa]] and to the northwest of [[American Canyon, California|American Canyon]] on the [[West Napa Fault]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://m.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Boats-grapes-and-Poseidon-at-Napa-quake-s-5714272.php|title = Boats, grapes and Poseidon at Napa quake's epicenter|last = Fimrite|first = Peter|date = August 27, 2014|work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate = 2 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nTotal damage in the southern [[Napa County, California|Napa Valley]] and [[Vallejo, California|Vallejo]] areas was in the range of $362 million to $1 billion, with one person killed and 200 injured. Other aspects of the event included an experimental [[earthquake warning system]] that alerted seismologists several seconds before the damaging [[S-wave|shear waves]] arrived, temporary changes in springs and wells, and the potential for [[wikt:postseismic|postseismic]] [[aseismic creep|fault creep]].\n\n==Tectonic setting==\n{{see also|California earthquake forecast|Strike-slip tectonics}}\n\nThe [[San Andreas Fault|San Andreas Fault System]] is an active plate boundary comprising [[Sinistral and dextral#Geology|right-lateral]] [[Fault (geology)#Strike-slip faults|strike-slip]] faults that runs nearly the length of California. This network of faults trends north-northwest in the area of the [[West Napa Fault]], where it is {{convert|80|km|order=flip}} wide from west to east. The West Napa Fault transfers slip between a group of related faults (including the [[Concord Fault]] and the [[Calaveras Fault]]) called the Contra Costa Shear Zone, which was assigned a maximum slip rate of 1mm/yr in the third Uniform California Earthquake Rupture Forecast. The authors of a separate study that focused on [[Global Positioning System]] data gave an estimated slip rate of 4\u00b13mm/yr for the West Napa Fault.<ref name=Brocher>{{citation|title=The Mw 6.0 24 August 2014 South Napa Earthquake |url=https://seismo.berkeley.edu/~rallen/pub/2015brocher/BrocherEtAl-SRL-2015.pdf|first=T. M.|last=Brocher|first2=A. S.|last2=Baltay|first3=J. L.|last3=Hardebeck|authorlink3=Jeanne L. Hardebeck|first4=F. F.|last4=Pollitz|first5=J. R.|last5=Murray|first6=A. L.|last6=Llenos|first7=D. P.|last7=Schwartz|first8=J. L.|last8=Blair|first9=D. J.|last9=Ponti|first10=J. J.|last10=Lienkaemper|first11=V. E.|last11=Langenheim|first12=T. E.|last12=Dawson|first13=K. W.|last13=Hudnut|first14=D. R.|last14=Shelly|first15=D. S.|last15=Dreger|first16=J.|last16=Boatright|first17=B. T|last17=Aagaard|first18=D. J.|last18=Wald|first19=R. M.|last19=Allen|first20=W. D.|last20=Barnhart|first21=K. L.|last21=Knudsen|first22=B. A.|last22=Brooks|first23=K. M.|last23=Scharer|year=2015|journal=Seismological Research Letters|volume=86|number=2A|page=309|doi=10.1785/0220150004 }}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Active Faults of the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aQUgAwAAQBAJ|last=Yeats|first=R.|date=2012|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0521190855|pages=82, 83}}</ref>\n\n==Earthquake==\nThe mainshock was magnitude 6.0, with a depth of 11.3&nbsp;km.<ref name=usgs /> The [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS) estimated that 15,000 people experienced severe shaking, 106,000 people felt very strong shaking, 176,000 felt strong shaking, and 738,000 felt moderate shaking.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> The earthquake lasted 10 to 20 seconds, depending on location.<ref name=\"latimes.lanow\" /> At least twelve aftershocks followed, including one of magnitude 3.9.<ref name=\"aftersh\">{{Cite news|last = Rossmann|first = Randi|title = 3.9M aftershock rattles Napa|journal = [[The Press Democrat]]|location = Santa Rosa|date = August 26, 2014|url = http://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/2591205-181/napa-rattled-by-39m-aftershock|accessdate = 2014-08-27|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140903085339/http://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/2591205-181/napa-rattled-by-39m-aftershock|archive-date = September 3, 2014|url-status = dead|df = mdy-all}}</ref>  The earthquake was the largest earthquake in the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]] since the magnitude 6.9 [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake]].<ref name=\"latimes.lanow\">{{cite news |title=After earthquake near Napa, up to 100 homes labeled unfit to enter|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-quake-near-napa-jolts-bay-area-20140824-story.html |author=Lee Romney |author2=Ryan Parker |author3=Christine Mai-Duc |author4=Lauren Raab|accessdate=August 25, 2014 |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 24, 2014}}</ref> Governor [[Jerry Brown]] declared a [[State of emergency#United States|state of emergency]] due to the severe damage and the possibility of aftershocks.<ref name=\"wsj 14:23 ET\">{{cite news|title=Strong Earthquake Shakes Northern California|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/6-0-earthquake-shakes-northern-california-1408882575|accessdate=August 24, 2014|publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=August 24, 2014}}</ref> [[President Obama]] declared a major disaster for Napa and Solano counties.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Napa-quake-Obama-declares-major-disaster-5749556.php|title = Napa quake: Obama declares major disaster, freeing up aid|last = Williams|first = Kate|date = September 15, 2014|work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate = 2 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Damage===\n\nSeveral older commercial buildings in downtown Napa showed signs of extensive external damage even though many had been retrofitted for earthquake safety protection.<ref name=cnn>{{cite news |author=Josh Levs |author2=Susanna Capelouto |author3=Joshua Berlinger |last-author-amp=yes |title= Northern California earthquake is area's strongest in 25 years |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/08/24/us/california-earthquake/ |accessdate=August 25, 2014 |work=CNN |date=August 24, 2014}}</ref> The [[Goodman Library]], [[Napa County Courthouse Plaza]], [[Sam Kee Laundry Building]], [[U.S. Post Office (Napa, California)|Downtown U.S. Post Office]], [[Alexandria Hotel and Annex]], [[Native Sons of the Golden West]] building,<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Yune| first = Howard | title = Earthquake damage repaired, Napa's Native Sons building shines again| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = March 20, 2018| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/earthquake-damage-repaired-napa-s-native-sons-building-shines-again/article_5d139ead-34e6-559d-93b0-6f60f2edda89.html#tracking-source=home-top-story| accessdate = March 21, 2018}}</ref> First United Methodist Church, and [[First Presbyterian Church (Napa, California)|First Presbyterian Church]] all suffered moderate to extensive damage.<ref name=\"PD-NPB\">{{Cite news|last1= Moore |first1= Derek |last2= Rossmann |first2= Randi |date= August 14, 2014 |title= Napa's people, buildings hit hard by 6.0 earthquake |url= http://www.pressdemocrat.com/home/2575107-181/napas-people-buildings-hit-hard |newspaper= [[The Press Democrat]]|location= Santa Rosa |accessdate= 2014-08-25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2014 South Napa eathquake Alexandria Square building.jpg|thumb|left|Damaged Alexandria Square building in Napa]]\n\nAll of these buildings are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]. Although the structure of the [[Uptown Theater (Napa, California)|Uptown Theater]] was determined to be sound, the building was [[Color-tagged structure|red-tagged]] due to damage to the theater's ceiling.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = Uptown to remain closed until November| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 11, 2014| url =http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/uptown-to-remain-closed-until-november/article_a75ae773-4591-5db2-bbae-1ed7f0813481.html| accessdate = September 11, 2014}}</ref>  Several newer commercial buildings also suffered damage.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = Damaged businesses struggle to reopen| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = August 25, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/damaged-businesses-struggle-to-reopen/article_a5f0c5ab-1c09-5a4d-8cd0-26e3d09ddf6b.html| accessdate = August 26, 2014}}</ref>  Six major fires broke out,<ref name=\"cnn\" /> and four homes in Napa Valley Mobile Home Park located in north Napa were destroyed.  Firefighters were hampered in their efforts to fight this fire by a broken water main.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Wetzstein| first = Janelle | title = Shattered property, bruised lives| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = August 24, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/shattered-property-bruised-lives/article_1af7d38c-2d23-532d-a9da-b2c5c9e3def4.html| accessdate = August 26, 2014}}</ref> In Vallejo, several hundred storefront windows shattered and many building walls suffered extensive damage. A water main on [[Mare Island]] broke.<ref name=fimritevallejo>Fimrite, Peter. [http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Northern-California-earthquake-Blue-collar-5711775.php Northern California earthquake: Blue-collar Vallejo hit hard], ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', August 26, 2014.</ref>\n\nFollowing the first round of building inspections by the City of Napa inspectors, a total of 613 structures had been tagged; 113 were red-tagged and 500 had been yellow-tagged.<ref>{{Cite journal| last =  Polson| first = Burt| title = A red-tagged building and a tenant| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 1, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/business/columnists/burt-polson/a-red-tagged-building-and-a-tenant/article_f8a06146-85fb-5bca-bacf-8dae22c9f357.html| accessdate = September 11, 2014}}</ref> Pavement on several roads in [[Napa County|Napa]], [[Solano County|Solano]] and [[Sonoma County|Sonoma]] Counties buckled and cracked during the quake.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Cabanatuan| first = Michael| title = Earthquake cracks, buckles roads, but leaves bridges OK| journal = [[SF Gate]]| location = Napa, CA| date = August 24, 2014| url = http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Quake-buckles-cracks-roads-but-leaves-bridges-5709018.php| accessdate = August 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWithin days, County officials estimated the damage at $362 million.<ref name=\"362 million\">{{Cite news|last = Carter|first = Lori|title = Napa quake damage rises to $362 million |journal = [[The Press Democrat]]|location = Santa Rosa|date = August 28, 2014|url = http://www.pressdemocrat.com/home/2613337-181/napa-quake-damage-rises-to|accessdate = 2014-08-28 }}</ref>  According to an early estimate by the USGS, the economic costs to Napa County may go as high as $1 billion.<ref name=latimeseconomic>Stevens, Matt. [http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-napa-earthquake-damage-cost-20140825-story.html Napa, Calif., earthquake: Economic hit could reach $1 billion], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', August 25, 2014.</ref> Several wineries including Hess Collection and [[Trefethen Vineyards]] suffered damage to buildings and infrastructure.  Several wine storage facilities also suffered damage and loss of property.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Paulsen| first = Sasha| title = Wine industry tallies spilled wine, shattered barrels| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = August 25, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/wine-industry-tallies-spilled-wine-shattered-barrels/article_bb75cbb0-dab2-5211-ad1c-fafd5367e854.html| accessdate = August 25, 2014}}</ref>  Estimates of the damage to the wine industry were downgraded to between $80 and $100 million in a September 5, 2014 report from [[Silicon Valley Bank]] to the Napa County Board of Supervisors.<ref>{{Cite journal| last =  Jensen| first = Peter| title = Napa quakes causes $80 million blow to wine industry, report says| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 9, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/napa-quakes-causes-million-blow-to-wine-industry-report-says/article_dc263bc9-41a8-5282-adf4-adafc8d04181.html| accessdate = September 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, 2014 in a report to the Napa City Council, members were briefed on the status of damage sustained.  City Staff reported that 156 commercial and residential structures had been red-tagged and 1398 had been yellow-tagged.  It was also reported that the estimate for damage to the City's infrastructure had reached $57.9 million.  This total included repairs made to 144 water mains, repairs or replacement of a compromised water tank in Brown's Valley that is part of the City's water system and repair of 294 locations where streets and sidewalks had been damaged.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Ynue| first = Howard| title = Napa tallies earthquake damage across city| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 17, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/napa-tallies-earthquake-damage-across-city/article_82e2905c-4b2d-545c-a856-180e668a8613.html| accessdate = September 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shake Intensity - 2014 South Napa Earthquake.jpg|thumb|USGS ShakeMap for the event]]\n\n===Injuries===\nAbout 200 injured people were treated at [[Queen of the Valley Medical Center (Napa, California)|Queen of the Valley Medical Center]] in Napa.<ref name=\"PD-NPB\"/> Thirteen of those injured were admitted. Nicholas Dillon was gravely injured after many bricks from a chimney fell on him.<ref name=\"kgo7 4:45 PDT\" /> Many of the injuries were lacerations and abrasions from fallen debris.<ref name=\"cnn\" /> At least six of the injuries were classified as critical.<ref name=\"kgo7 4:45 PDT\">[[KGO-TV]] report from Queen of the Valley Medical Center, 4:45 pm</ref> In Vallejo, 49 people were injured, including two who were hospitalized.<ref name=fimritevallejo/> CNN reported one individual still in critical condition, later discovery determined as a 58-year-old male who went through two surgeries, awakening four days later in ICU to discover it was going to take him approximately two years to learn how to walk again. One person died September 5 as a result of injuries from the quake.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-napa-woman-dies-napa-earthquake-toppled-tv-20140910-story.html |title=Napa earthquake death: 2 weeks later, quake claims first victim -|journal=LA Times |author= Rong-Gong Lin II|website= |accessdate=2014-09-10|date=September 10, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last =  Todorov| first = Kerana| title = First earthquake-related death reported| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 9, 2014| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/first-earthquake-related-death-reported/article_df5e8346-0239-5651-916a-ec5f991aae51.html#| accessdate = September 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Recovery===\nSeveral of the historic buildings damaged in the earthquake have been repaired while others are still awaiting renovation and restoration.  The Uptown Theater was the first to reopen on November 9, 2014.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Yune| first = Howard| title = Crumbled by Napa earthquake, Uptown Theatre mural rises again| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = November 17, 2014| url =http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/crumbled-by-napa-earthquake-uptown-theatre-mural-rises-again/article_0208cd23-bb5b-5001-bdd9-891811fcc7bc.html| accessdate = November 17, 2014}}</ref>  The congregation of the First Presbyterian Church moved back into the sanctuary in July 2016 following repairs and restoration at a cost of $850,000.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = First Presbyterian church returns to quake-damaged sanctuary after almost two years| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = July 9, 2016| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/first-presbyterian-church-returns-to-quake-damaged-sanctuary-after-almost/article_1ae0b8d3-db2c-5dcd-9c65-dd702ff5b990.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> The United Methodist Church received $2.2 million in repairs and upgrades and reopened the doors to its congregation in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = Churches repair and reopen after quake| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = August 23, 2015| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/churches-repair-and-reopen-after-quake/article_7c94b89e-7e81-57c1-8993-d407b853355b.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Yune| first = Howard| title = After earthquake repairs, Napa Methodist church to reopen Sunday| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = November 17, 2015| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/after-earthquake-repairs-napa-methodist-church-to-reopen-sunday/article_7e23295c-1a88-53dc-83ab-1c6fb3ec25a7.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> A $1.75 million contract to repair damage to the Goodman Library was awarded in January 2017 and work on the building is expected to be completed in early 2018.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Yune| first = Howard| title = Napa awards repair contract for quake-damaged Goodman Library| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = January 25, 2017| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/eagle/news/local/napa-awards-repair-contract-for-quake-damaged-goodman-library/article_9fcd7f88-f5a2-5cf4-a168-3410100c6f0c.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service]] determined that repairing the building would be too costly and sold it to a developer for $2 million.  The developer plans to turn the building into a hotel.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Huffman| first = Jennifer| title = Napa's old post office sold for $2 million for a hotel| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = March 10, 2017| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/damaged-businesses-struggle-to-reopen/article_a5f0c5ab-1c09-5a4d-8cd0-26e3d09ddf6b.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> An $11.6 million contract for restoration of the courthouse was awarded by [[Napa County]] in August 2017.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Eberling| first = Barry| title = Repair of earthquake damage to Napa courthouse to start soon| journal = [[Napa Valley Register]] | publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = September 1, 2017| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/repair-of-earthquake-damage-to-napa-courthouse-to-start-soon/article_3d5af16a-47b7-51bb-8da2-f79f9cf1e0cc.html| accessdate = September 2, 2017}}</ref> The heavily damaged Trefethen Vineyard Eschol building was restored from earthquake damage following over two years of repairs and improvements.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Lander| first = Jess|title = Trefethen rebounds after the earthquake |journal = [[Napa Valley Register]]| publisher = Lee Enterprises, Inc.| location = Napa, CA| date = March 30, 2017| url = http://napavalleyregister.com/wine/trefethen-rebounds-after-the-earthquake/article_979ac4fb-dfa7-535e-904a-2a1c3ab640f3.html| accessdate = April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hydrologic effects===\nThe event was credited with large, temporary increases in the water flow of several nearby streams, including [[Carriger Creek (Sonoma County, California)|Carriger Creek]], Calabasas Creek, Felder Creek, [[Sonoma Creek]], Tulocay Creek, Green Valley Creek, and Wild Horse Creek.  In addition, the water levels of several wells in the [[Sonoma Valley]] rose suddenly at the time of the quake, in one instance by {{Convert|5|feet}}.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Napa quake jumpstarts stream flows, though probably only temporarily |date=September 4, 2014 |url=http://www.pressdemocrat.com/home/2655382-181/napa-quake-jumpstarts-stream-flows|last=Kovner|first=Guy|accessdate=September 4, 2014|work=[[The Press Democrat]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.sfgate.com/science/article/Surprise-bonanza-since-Napa-quake-dry-creeks-now-5739098.php|title = Surprise bonanza since Napa quake: dry creeks now flowing|last = Fimrite|first = Peter|date = September 6, 2014|work = San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate = 7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Fault creep===\n{{Further|Aseismic creep}}\n\nIn the following months, geologists studying the effects of the event warned that a potential afterslip could cause the previously unmapped portion of the fault in the Browns Valley area of Napa to slowly move up to another {{convert|6|in|mm}} in the next 3 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-quake-napa-fault-20141217-story.html |title=After big quake, Napa fault could move 6 inches in 3 years |journal=LA Times |date=December 17, 2014 |author= Rong-Gong Lin II |author2= Rosanna Xia |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-quake-napa-fault-20141226-story.html#page=1 |title=Napa's surprise fault line triggers earthquake study of the region |journal=LA Times |date=December 26, 2014 |author= Rong-Gong Lin II |author2= Rosanna Xia |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==Earthquake warning==\n{{Main|ShakeAlert}}\nAn experimental [[earthquake warning system]] being developed by the [[Berkeley Seismological Laboratory]] issued a warning upon detecting the [[P-wave]]s five seconds before the slower, more destructive [[S-wave]]s arrived in Berkeley. Initially this was reported to be a 10-second warning in Berkeley,<ref name=cbs>{{cite news|title=Experimental warning system gave 10-second alert before California earthquake |work=[[CBS News]] |date=August 24, 2014 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/experimental-warning-system-gave-10-second-alert-before-quake-hit/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6S5x6f9mE?url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/experimental-warning-system-gave-10-second-alert-before-quake-hit/ |archivedate=August 25, 2014 |url-status=live|df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = In Latest Calif. Earthquake, Shake Alert Tests Its Legs|url = https://www.npr.org/2014/08/25/343203813/in-latest-calif-earthquake-shake-alert-tests-its-legs|website = NPR|accessdate = 2015-08-23|first = Melissa|last = Block}}</ref> but revised information indicates only a 5-second warning was provided.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Allen|first1=Richard M.|last2=Given|first2=Douglas D.|last3=Heaton|first3=Thomas H.|authorlink3=Thomas H. Heaton|last4=Vidale|first4=John E.|authorlink4=John Vidale|title=Successful ShakeAlert Performance for the Napa Quake|journal=2014 AGU Fall Meeting|volume=44|date=2014|issue=S44D\u201301|pages=S44D\u201301|bibcode=2014AGUFM.S44D..01A}}</ref> This means the S-waves had already arrived in Napa and Vallejo when the warning was issued.\n\nSeismic Warning Systems, Inc., a private earthquake warning company based in [[Scotts Valley, California|Scotts Valley, CA]], had installed on-site warning systems at five fire stations in Vallejo in 2002 and 2003.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wurman|first1=Gilead|last2=Price|first2=Michael J.|title=Earthquake Warning Performance in Vallejo for the South Napa Quake|journal=2014 AGU Fall Meeting|date=2014|issue=S33F\u20134937|location=San Francisco, CA}}</ref> These systems commanded the bay doors to open at these fire stations between 1.7 and 2.4 seconds before the S-waves arrived at each fire station.\n\nEarthquake warning systems could potentially give people time to take cover in the event of a quake, preventing injuries caused by falling debris, automatically stopping trains or shutting off gas lines. The system being developed at the Berkeley Seismological Laboratory (called [[ShakeAlert]]) in conjunction with the [[United States Geological Survey]], the [[California Institute of Technology]] and the [[University of Washington]], will eventually cover the entire West Coast. The system would cost $80 million in funding to run for five years in California, or $120 million for the whole West Coast.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/early-warning-system-in-testing-sounded-alarm-before-quake-1408999597|title = Expanding Earthquake Warning System May Help the Public|last = Elinson|first = Zusha|date = 25 August 2014|work = Wall Street Journal|accessdate = 26 August 2014}}</ref> In December 2014, [[United States Congress]] approved a $5 million allocation as part of the [[Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2014]] in order to expand funding for development of the system.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-quake-early-warning-20141215-story.html |title=California receives U.S. funding for earthquake early-warning system- LA Times |date=December 14, 2014 |author= Rong-Gong Lin II|work= |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n* [[List of earthquakes in 2014]]\n* [[List of earthquakes in California]]\n* [[List of earthquakes in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|32em|refs=\n<ref name=usgs>{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/nc72282711#summary|title=M6.0 \u2013 6km NW of American Canyon, California|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|author=USGS}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|24 August 2014 earthquake centered in Napa, California, USA}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jddUOtyz9zk SCEC's Response to the South Napa Earthquake] \u2013 [[Southern California Earthquake Center]]\n* [https://www.llnl.gov/sites/default/files/field/file/South_Napa_slides.pdf The August 24, 2014 South Napa Earthquake: What Is Known So Far, Accessing Open Information And Preliminary Ground Motion Simulations] \u2013 [[Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory]]\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28918600 California earthquake strikes San Francisco Bay area] \u2013 ''[[BBC News]]''\n* [https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/08/24/us-usaearthquake-idUSKBN0GO0A520140824 Quake rocks California wine country, dozens injured] \u2013 [[Reuters]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140826113933/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/research/external/reports/05HQAG0002.pdf Mapping of the West Napa Fault Zone for input into the Northern California Quaternary fault database]\n* {{EQ-isc-link|610572079}}\n* [http://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/8433959-181/study-2014-napa-quake-may Study: 2014 Napa quake may be linked to groundwater changes]\n\n{{Earthquakes in 2014}}\n{{Earthquakes in California}}\n{{Earthquakes in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:South Napa Earthquake, 2014}}\n[[Category:2014 earthquakes]]\n[[Category:2014 in California]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in California|2014]]\n[[Category:Geology of Napa County, California]]\n[[Category:History of Napa County, California]]\n[[Category:History of Solano County, California]]\n", "name_user": "NASCARfan0548", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"Earthquake in California in 2014\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_South_Napa_earthquake"}
